I don't know what this means.  Is this some internal code-name that you didn't mean to put out here?

Onyx is internal code name . 
This patch need rework , once the requiered devtree support is in place Kerenl/uboot.

sp5 refers to the socket and onyx is the reference board. Our Goal is to create a single binary image for all sp5 socket reference boards. There are 4 reference boards - Onyx, Quartz, Ruby and Titanite. We internally create a single image by loading a different dts based on the board ID in FRU. [Differentiation happens at Runtime instead of compile time].
As a starting point, we want to upstream support for Onyx reference board which belongs to SP5 socket family.
I don't think this exists in the upstream tree.
Not available now, working on upstream support
Patch has been sent. awaiting review as of now.
I don't think this exists.

Why is this considered "nohost"?  That usually means that the platform doesn't have a managed host, but I'm pretty sure you have an AMD processor running a real managed host / OS, right?

No-host introduced to validate the CRB with minimal functionalities. This patch Host specific functionalities are disabled. will enabling full functiolalites in later commits once all the required recipies in.
Would suggest putting this into an conf/machine/include file for all AMD platforms rather than a one-off OVERRIDE you put into all platforms.
